1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:11,220
Today I’m helping you with your trading mindset. 
Your mindset is made up of all the established  

2
00:00:11,220 --> 00:00:15,840
beliefs and attitudes you default to, 
internally, when it comes to trading.  

3
00:00:16,380 --> 00:00:20,160
And speaking from experience, a 
change in mindset is one of the  

4
00:00:20,160 --> 00:00:25,020
hardest things to achieve. But when you 
do it, trading will become a lot easier. 

5
00:00:25,680 --> 00:00:31,260
It’s gonna be interesting. So, like, subscribe, 
and stick around for the full video.
  

6
00:00:31,260 --> 00:00:36,360
Trading is more about people than prices
Trading  

7
00:00:36,360 --> 00:00:43,260
is as much about game theory than any underlying 
economics. You don’t make money by predicting  

8
00:00:43,260 --> 00:00:49,080
performance, you make money by predicting how 
people respond to changes in a particular market. 

9
00:00:49,920 --> 00:00:55,980
There’s a common saying: the market has memory.
Well, I would say the market participants,  

10
00:00:55,980 --> 00:01:00,180
the crowd, have memory.
Optimism and pessimism,  

11
00:01:00,180 --> 00:01:07,500
hope and fear—all these emotions can exist in one 
trader at different times or in multiple traders  

12
00:01:07,500 --> 00:01:11,580
or groups at the same time.
The market psychology is  

13
00:01:11,580 --> 00:01:18,060
steering market trends and price action.
Reading market trends and market psychology can  

14
00:01:18,060 --> 00:01:24,240
be extremely hard for a beginner. But it can be 
done if you analyze volume and the open interest. 

15
00:01:25,080 --> 00:01:29,040
You will be in a much better 
position to assess the mood of the  

16
00:01:29,040 --> 00:01:35,580
market and adjust your position accordingly.
So remember, trading is a game with your own  

17
00:01:35,580 --> 00:01:42,300
rules, a game of psychology and discipline. 
Numbers, analysis, data etc are secondary.

18
00:01:42,300 --> 00:01:47,460
What drives your decision-making? 

19
00:01:47,460 --> 00:01:52,380
Each one of us has a unique risk 
tolerance. Some are more aggressive,  

20
00:01:52,380 --> 00:01:58,860
some more conservative or analytical.
I’ve said many times, make sure you  

21
00:01:58,860 --> 00:02:03,300
use a strategy that fits your risk 
profile and fits your daily schedule. 

22
00:02:04,080 --> 00:02:08,760
Many traders fail because of their 
inability to understand themselves. 

23
00:02:08,760 --> 00:02:13,380
You need to ask yourself some questions:
• How do you handle stress? 

24
00:02:13,380 --> 00:02:18,060
• How do you deal with uncertainties?
• Can you cope with losses? 

25
00:02:18,060 --> 00:02:24,180
• Do you get euphoric after substantial gains?
• Can you detach from money? 

26
00:02:24,180 --> 00:02:27,840
• Are you patient?
• Are you flexible and  

27
00:02:27,840 --> 00:02:31,800
willing to change during a trade?
• Can you admit being wrong? 

28
00:02:32,820 --> 00:02:35,460
These questions are related to fear,  

29
00:02:35,460 --> 00:02:39,360
greed, and the adrenaline that 
interfere almost on a daily basis. 

30
00:02:40,020 --> 00:02:45,300
Answer to them honestly, and try to 
understand what drives your decision-making.

31
00:02:45,300 --> 00:02:50,460
Your dominant personality traits will 
sooner or later influence your trading 

32
00:02:50,460 --> 00:02:57,180
Let’s make a quick exercise. Write down your 
strengths and weaknesses when it comes to trading. 

33
00:02:57,780 --> 00:03:03,240
Look at yourself from a distance and try 
to be as objective and neutral as possible. 

34
00:03:03,840 --> 00:03:10,140
By putting your traits down on paper, you force 
yourself to express your thoughts clearly. 

35
00:03:10,680 --> 00:03:15,720
In my case, as strengths I’ve 
wrote down: analytical mindset,  

36
00:03:15,720 --> 00:03:21,180
self control, very organized and 
logical, passionate for trading.  

37
00:03:21,840 --> 00:03:29,820
And as weaknesses: inability to be 100% detached 
from money when I’m in a live trade, not the  

38
00:03:29,820 --> 00:03:36,720
most patient trader when I’m scalping, the need to 
perfection sometimes affects my trading decisions. 

39
00:03:37,620 --> 00:03:43,920
It’s a simple exercise aiming at understanding 
your personality traits, and your strength  

40
00:03:43,920 --> 00:03:51,060
and weaknesses. In the end, all your dominant 
personality traits will sooner or later influence  

41
00:03:51,060 --> 00:03:57,540
your trading and thus your profits (or losses).
So do yourself a favor, and think about your  

42
00:03:57,540 --> 00:04:03,180
personality type. And build your trading 
around your strengths, not your weaknesses.

43
00:04:03,180 --> 00:04:08,880
No trade and no strategy is perfect 

44
00:04:08,880 --> 00:04:14,100
Expecting the perfect entry or exit, 
or expecting to catch the full wave,  

45
00:04:14,100 --> 00:04:19,200
are things that are incredibly 
rare. I still struggle with this. 

46
00:04:19,200 --> 00:04:25,200
Most of your trades will be far from perfect 
and this is the tough reality of trading. 

47
00:04:25,860 --> 00:04:29,820
If you expect perfection, you will 
suffer through a lot of frustration. 

48
00:04:29,820 --> 00:04:35,580
And it goes without saying but, also, 
there is no perfect trading strategy. 

49
00:04:35,580 --> 00:04:39,900
A perfect trading strategy is one 
that makes money in the long run,  

50
00:04:39,900 --> 00:04:46,320
not a system that makes money with every trade.
You may already have a profitable trading  

51
00:04:46,320 --> 00:04:51,060
strategy in your hands, you just don’t 
know it because after every losing trade,  

52
00:04:51,060 --> 00:04:56,760
you change it or you want to adjust it so that 
the loss you just took could have been avoided. 

53
00:04:57,480 --> 00:05:03,060
However, changing your system means you’re 
opening it to other potential losses. 

54
00:05:03,600 --> 00:05:09,600
Accepting that no trade and no strategy 
is perfect relieves you of a giant burden.

55
00:05:09,600 --> 00:05:14,340
Things rarely ever go according to plan 

56
00:05:14,340 --> 00:05:21,000
Let’s face it, things rarely ever go according 
to plan, even if you are organized and prepared. 

57
00:05:21,540 --> 00:05:27,240
If you refuse to accept this reality and if you 
don’t work tirelessly on a solid trading plan  

58
00:05:27,240 --> 00:05:34,140
with an effective action plan that covers as many 
possibilities as you might run into while trading,  

59
00:05:34,140 --> 00:05:40,560
you are not going to survive as a trader.
When you trade, it’s imperative that you know  

60
00:05:40,560 --> 00:05:46,860
what risks you’re willing to take and how you will 
manage them if something goes wrong along the way. 

61
00:05:47,760 --> 00:05:52,320
In trading, all uncontrolled 
elements are considered risks.  

62
00:05:52,320 --> 00:05:57,120
These are the factors that can 
always go against your trade. 

63
00:05:57,120 --> 00:06:03,840
On the other hand, controlled elements are the 
tools that help you restrain and reduce the risks.

64
00:06:03,840 --> 00:06:08,520
Know what you can and can’t control in trading 

65
00:06:08,520 --> 00:06:12,900
So let’s talk about controlled and 
uncontrolled elements in trading. 

66
00:06:13,620 --> 00:06:20,820
Your analysis is the first controlled element.
You control how thorough your analysis is. If  

67
00:06:20,820 --> 00:06:26,640
you invest the proper time and knowledge into it, 
you’ll be able to come away with a well-educated  

68
00:06:26,640 --> 00:06:32,820
analysis and assessment of a market.
Timing The Entry / Exit is another  

69
00:06:32,820 --> 00:06:37,140
obvious controlled element.
You get to make the decision for  

70
00:06:37,140 --> 00:06:43,920
where and when to act in the market and at what 
price to place your positions, targets, and stops. 

71
00:06:44,820 --> 00:06:52,020
The market and Time frame You Trade are also under 
your control. You decide when, where, how long,  

72
00:06:52,020 --> 00:06:58,920
and under what settings you want to trade in.
Another controlled element: Risk-Reward. It’s  

73
00:06:58,920 --> 00:07:05,160
your decision to filter out trades that are not 
deemed to provide a sufficient risk-reward ratio. 

74
00:07:05,760 --> 00:07:10,920
Position Sizing, another controlled 
element. You decide how much you risk  

75
00:07:10,920 --> 00:07:16,740
on a position. It’s at your discretion 
to set the margin for error and drawdown. 

76
00:07:17,460 --> 00:07:23,280
You can also time how to secure your exposed 
position during major economic releases.  

77
00:07:23,940 --> 00:07:28,680
The schedule of these events are 
pre-planned and published ahead of time,  

78
00:07:28,680 --> 00:07:36,780
so you have plenty of time to stay out, set stops 
and targets, reduce exposure or any other mean of  

79
00:07:36,780 --> 00:07:43,200
protection from the upcoming high volatility.
Training Your Psychological State is another  

80
00:07:43,200 --> 00:07:49,620
thing which is somewhat under your control.
Knowing your mental strengths and what you  

81
00:07:49,620 --> 00:07:55,020
can put to use. This also means being aware 
of the mental weakness you need to work on. 

82
00:07:55,920 --> 00:08:00,540
Capping your risk is also something 
that’s definitely done by your decision.  

83
00:08:01,140 --> 00:08:06,060
So are shifting and securing profits 
with stops and setting stop loss and  

84
00:08:06,060 --> 00:08:10,140
targets in realistic locations, 
relative to the market conditions.

85
00:08:10,860 --> 00:08:16,080
All these elements are under your control. 
But how about elements you can’t control. 

86
00:08:16,920 --> 00:08:22,200
The trigger condition is the first one.
You can never time when all the right  

87
00:08:22,200 --> 00:08:28,980
conditions align to trigger a trade (or an 
exit). This sometimes results in doing things  

88
00:08:28,980 --> 00:08:35,220
like missing the entry and jumping late on 
a trade or prematurely entering a trade. 

89
00:08:36,600 --> 00:08:39,720
Available information is 
another uncontrolled element. 

90
00:08:40,440 --> 00:08:45,060
As a retail trader, you are always 
on the short end of receiving the  

91
00:08:45,060 --> 00:08:48,720
relevant information that can 
affect your trade assessment. 

92
00:08:48,720 --> 00:08:54,660
For example, information such as increasing 
volume is not available for forex trading. 

93
00:08:54,660 --> 00:09:01,800
Retail traders like you and me are left only 
with little information, such as chart reading  

94
00:09:01,800 --> 00:09:07,800
and macroeconomic data. We simply don’t have 
an information edge. And this is a risk. 

95
00:09:08,520 --> 00:09:15,780
Price Volatility is also out of your control.
When price moves in a strong manner, you can only  

96
00:09:15,780 --> 00:09:22,800
see it after it happens. It’s almost impossible 
to get a heads-up before a major move occurs,  

97
00:09:23,640 --> 00:09:29,100
and your position will always be exposed 
to such rough events at any given time. 

98
00:09:29,100 --> 00:09:35,040
Once you are in a trade, while the price moves, 
you cannot really do anything as it happens. 

99
00:09:35,880 --> 00:09:40,740
The same thing goes for unexpected 
news events that affect our positions.  

100
00:09:41,340 --> 00:09:47,940
You can never know when they’re about to erupt 
and in which direction they’ll move the market in. 

101
00:09:47,940 --> 00:09:52,500
Also, setting trade targets does 
not guarantee prices will reach it  

102
00:09:52,500 --> 00:09:59,400
before they reach your stop loss. We have no 
control over what direction the market takes.  

103
00:09:59,400 --> 00:10:05,340
If you’re aiming for a specific RRR, it’s 
not guaranteed you will get it as expected. 

104
00:10:06,180 --> 00:10:11,280
Your psychological readiness for 
specific events can hit you by surprise. 

105
00:10:11,280 --> 00:10:15,420
Life Circumstances is 
another uncontrolled element. 

106
00:10:15,420 --> 00:10:22,620
Maybe you’re having a bad day, or you’re facing 
a challenging period in your life, you’re tired,  

107
00:10:22,620 --> 00:10:29,100
or demotivated. Life circumstances will not 
always be optimal to support your trading. 

108
00:10:29,940 --> 00:10:35,040
The point is: always acknowledge that there 
are more aspects that you’re not aware of,  

109
00:10:35,040 --> 00:10:40,920
that will affect your trading and expose 
your position to risk. Acknowledge that  

110
00:10:40,920 --> 00:10:43,920
these events can pop out of 
the blue and surprise you. 

111
00:10:43,920 --> 00:10:49,500
Eventually, you will be able to spot 
new blind spots as they begin to form.

112
00:10:53,840 --> 00:10:54,840
You  

113
00:10:54,840 --> 00:10:57,360
are overtrading, and you don’t even know it
Overtrading is one of the most challenging  

114
00:10:57,360 --> 00:11:02,820
lessons for a trader to understand. If 
you tend to overtrade and you continue  

115
00:11:02,820 --> 00:11:09,420
to overtrade, you will lose a lot of money.
You expose your money to the market any time  

116
00:11:09,420 --> 00:11:15,240
you enter it. The fact is you could be 
overtrading, and you don’t even know it. 

117
00:11:15,240 --> 00:11:22,140
If you are overtrading, there are several signs:
- If you close a trade for a loss and you believe  

118
00:11:22,140 --> 00:11:27,480
deep down that you shouldn’t have taken 
the trade, you are guilty of overtrading. 

119
00:11:27,480 --> 00:11:34,080
- if you find yourself looking at lower time 
frames like the 5-minute chart and “discover”  

120
00:11:34,080 --> 00:11:40,860
some trades, even though you planned to use 
the H1 chart, again it’s a sign of overtrading 

121
00:11:40,860 --> 00:11:47,400
- if you’re spending too much time gazing 
at charts, you become vulnerable to seeing  

122
00:11:47,400 --> 00:11:52,020
too much market activity, which 
again, might turn into overtrading 

123
00:11:52,020 --> 00:11:58,680
- if you find yourself looking at charts for 
hours, attempting to “force” a trade, that  

124
00:11:58,680 --> 00:12:04,800
is not that obvious, because you don’t want to 
feel that you wasted time, again, a warning sign 

125
00:12:05,640 --> 00:12:12,120
The biggest issue is that many traders are clearly 
unaware that they are over-trading at the moment.  

126
00:12:12,780 --> 00:12:18,420
It is really possible to get fixated on 
a less-than-ideal trade setup, lose track  

127
00:12:18,420 --> 00:12:24,480
of your trading plan, and become uninformed 
about whether or not you are over-trading. 

128
00:12:25,080 --> 00:12:30,660
If you are guilty of this, it is best to 
go on the offensive against over-trading  

129
00:12:30,660 --> 00:12:36,960
and revisit your trading strategy and plan 
a better a trading schedule ahead of time.

130
00:12:36,960 --> 00:12:41,880
Not having a position is a position 

131
00:12:41,880 --> 00:12:49,260
The number of trades often does not translate 
into large profits. Instead, the effectiveness  

132
00:12:49,260 --> 00:12:56,760
of individual trades makes the real difference.
After a successful trade and a significant profit,  

133
00:12:56,760 --> 00:13:03,120
you can be tempted to continue trading, but the 
market doesn’t work according to your commands. 

134
00:13:03,120 --> 00:13:07,020
After a few successful 
trades, you may start losing. 

135
00:13:07,020 --> 00:13:12,900
Here’s a quick piece of advice: Set a limit 
on the number of trades you want to open in  

136
00:13:12,900 --> 00:13:18,360
a single day. Keep up with this plan, and 
if you feel like opening one more trade,  

137
00:13:18,360 --> 00:13:24,720
remind yourself that there is always tomorrow.
Again, I’ve said many times in the past,  

138
00:13:24,720 --> 00:13:32,880
not having a position is a position. Some of the 
best trades in life are the ones you do not take.

139
00:13:32,880 --> 00:13:38,400
Get rid of anything that doesn’t bring you value 

140
00:13:38,400 --> 00:13:45,600
Each one of us has different ways of understanding 
and processing trading situations. When we look at  

141
00:13:45,600 --> 00:13:51,240
a chart, we all see things differently and 
we experience the market events uniquely. 

142
00:13:51,840 --> 00:13:57,420
When you have a teacher or mentor, you can 
try to learn the concepts they share with you,  

143
00:13:57,420 --> 00:14:00,720
but you can’t expect to have the same results. 

144
00:14:00,720 --> 00:14:07,440
What works for them can contribute to your 
success, but in order to really succeed,  

145
00:14:07,440 --> 00:14:13,200
you will need to custom tailor everything you 
learn, to fit your special way of thinking. 

146
00:14:13,740 --> 00:14:19,620
This is why someone might trade supply and 
demand successfully, while you may be failing,  

147
00:14:19,620 --> 00:14:25,980
despite both of you using the same concepts.
Don’t just use a strategy just because it’s  

148
00:14:25,980 --> 00:14:32,580
popular, or you read somewhere that this is the 
best way to trade. Customize it to fit your need,  

149
00:14:32,580 --> 00:14:38,460
get rid of anything that doesn’t bring 
value and adjust it to your own beliefs.

150
00:14:39,780 --> 00:14:43,560
Now, if you’re looking to further 
improve your trading psychology  

151
00:14:43,560 --> 00:14:48,540
and correct more mistakes, this 
video will definitely help you.  

152
00:14:49,080 --> 00:14:55,080
And check out our academy program if you want to 
further level up your trading. Until next time!

